children.text: The site cut/earthworks have left an exposed, un-retained embankment that would require a retaining wall to properly support it.
The National Construction Code’s Building Code of Australia states in Section 3.1.1.1 Un-retained bulk earthworks, that

‘A site cut using an un-retained embankment must be within the allotment; and not within the zone of influence of any existing structure on the property, or the allotment boundary as defined in Table 3.1.1.1 and Figure 3.1.1.1a; and not deeper than 2m from the natural ground level at any point’ .

As the site cut/earthworks have resulted in an un-retained embankment that is outside of the slope ratio, or within the zone of influence, a retaining wall is required in order to meet the requirements of the BCA, and will require the builder engage the engineer to design such a retaining wall, and provide the owner with engineering and certification, and an updated building permit that includes the retaining wall works.
